title.narrative: Increased institutional coverage of the new ISTMO model in Central Government
Improved performance orientation of the budget

baseline.value: The budget document does not use program classifications with very limited financial performance information

target.value: Program budgeting approach is introduced in three pilot ministries for the 2018 budget year (budget for three ministries areprepared using program classification and financial and non-financial performance information)

actual.value: Target achieved. DIPRENA selected 3 sectors (Transport, Education and Health) to pilot program classfications. Consultancy work hasbeen done to review the budget classifications of these sectors.

title.narrative: Extended functional coverage of the new ISTMO model

baseline.value: The current SIAFPA does not include functionalities for budget preparation and is not harmonized with national payroll, procurementand public investment system

target.value: The new IFMIS model integrates functionalities for budget preparation, accounting, budget execution, treasury and accounting; withinterfaces with national debt, the treasury single account, and the e-tax system

actual.value: ISTMO includes all functions and integration with National Debt (SIGADE), Single Treasury Account, and e-Tax. However, the budgetformulation module of ISTMO is not being used due to resistance of budget unit in MEF. The 2019 budget was prepared in anapplication Fiori, which is integrated with ITSMO.

title.narrative: Increased institutional coverage of the new ISTMO model in Decentralized Government
Quality of public sector financial information improved

baseline.value: Financial reports do not provide complete information on government revenue and expenditures thus impeding the monitoring of budgetexecution

target.value: The government prepares through ISTMO and publishes within 6 months after the end of the fiscal year consolidated financialstatements of the Central Government

actual.value: Target has not been achieved. The MoF continues working on strengthening the quality and reliability of financial informationproduced at the institutional level needed for consolidation.

baseline.value: Law 22 (2006) and regulation 366 (2006). The law has changed 6 times between 2009 and 2014, but the regulation 366 has never beenmodified.

target.value: Updated procurement law (Law 61) and corresponding regulations (Decreto 40) establishing guiding principles for transparency,professionalization, and efficiency.

actual.value: Target has been achieved. Law 61, reforming public contracting in Panama, published September 27, 2017 in the Official Gazette(reforms the text of Law 22 of 2006). Executive Decree (Regulation) 40, published April 10, 2018 in the Official Gazette (replacesRegulation 366 of 2006).

title.narrative: Public entities increase the production and dissemination of performance information linked with budget information

baseline.value: Performance information is limited, not publicly available and not linked to financial information

target.value: Information on the budget associated with key performance indicators for 10 public sector entities is produced and publicallydisclosed.

actual.value: DIPRENA has indicated that 10 entities are being targeted for introducing results based budgeting in the formulation of the 2021national budget, which commences in early 2020. The expectation is that updated program information and performance indicators forthe 10 entities will be published for the 2021 budget in October 2020.

title.narrative: Increased use of ISTMO in Decentralized Government

baseline.value: SIAFPA, RAMAN, and all the previous information systems which supported the budget execution, were basically ex-post registrysystems. Implementation of ex-ante controls was not feasible

target.value: 75% of Decentralized Government’s Budget is subject to ISTMO controls and registration by Dec. 2019. (excluding transferences,Fondos Financieros, Payroll)

actual.value: 46% of Decentralized Entities´ budget is subject to ITSMO´s controls and regulation (excluding transfers, fondos financieros, andpayroll, and excluding Caja de Seguro Social)

title.narrative: Increased use of ISTMO in Central Government

baseline.value: SIAFPA, RAMAN, and all the previous information systems which supported the budget execution, were basically ex-post registrysystems. Implementation of ex-ante controls was not feasible

target.value: 75% of Central Government’s Budget is subject to ISTMO controls and registration by Dec. 2019. (excluding transfers, FondosFinancieros, payroll)

actual.value: Target is achieved. 100% of Central Government´s Budget is subject to ITSMO´s controls and regulation (excluding transfers, fondosfinancieros and payroll)

baseline.value: The current PanamaCompra system has no instruments to facilitate complaints about procurement processes

target.value: DGCP has implemented a procurement complaint module through PanamaCompra 3

actual.value: Panama Compra 3 Platform includes functionalities for managing complaints. Government expects to roll-out Panama Compra 3 by June20, 2020

baseline.value: 60% competitive procurement processes of Central and Decentralized Government are publicly and daily available through PanamaCompra2

target.value: 100% of competitive procurement processes of central and decentralized entities are publicly available through PanamaCompra 3 on adaily basis.

actual.value: Government expects to roll-out Panama Compra 3 to all entities by June 30, 2020
